{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534818"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:50:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:50:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15181"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15181"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.09,0.05,0.12,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104540"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7872"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86869"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"107"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19187"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104540"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical emergency team (MET) call is initiated by nursing staff for a 65-year-old woman with new tachycardia. She was admitted two days ago with cellulitis to her left lower leg. The nursing staff report that her heart rate has increased from 75/min to 130/min over the past two hours. She reports mild breathlessness but no chest pain. She has been receiving intravenous flucloxacillin and has been mostly bed-bound since admission due to pain. Her other medical history includes type 2 diabetes and hypertension. She is a current smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious. Her pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 90% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her chest is clear to auscultation. There is cellulitis on her left lower leg with associated tenderness and erythema which has receded from the marked outline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA full set of bloods, including venous blood gas, are sent during the MET call, which show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.45 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2 32 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate 22 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate 1.2 mmol/L (0.5-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 135 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 12.5 x 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 250 x 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 85 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her tachycardia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary embolism","Sepsis","Supraventricular tachycardia","Anxiety","Dehydration"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with new onset isolated tachycardia in the context of recent hospitalisation and immobility, which should raise suspicion for pulmonary embolism. The presence of mild hypoxia and respiratory alkalosis on blood gas (low pCO2) without other clinical findings further supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E commonly presents with isolated tachycardia, and risk factors in this case include recent hospitalisation and immobility. The Wells criteria for pulmonary embolism would classify this patient as having an intermediate or high probability based on these features. The normal lactate and respiratory alkalosis are most consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnxiety\u003C/strong\u003E may cause tachycardia and respiratory alkalosis from hyperventilation but would be unlikely to cause hypoxia. This should be a diagnosis of exclusion. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESepsis\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely given the absence of fever, normal blood pressure, normal lactate, and improving cellulitis. Her elevated white cell count is consistent with her known infection. While early sepsis can present with isolated tachycardia, the clinical picture is more consistent with pulmonary embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupraventricular tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a sudden onset of rapid, regular tachycardia, often with rates above 150/min. It would be unusual to have associated hypoxia in the absence of hypotension, and the gradual onset over two hours makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDehydration\u003C/strong\u003E severe enough to cause this degree of tachycardia would typically present with other signs such as hypotension, dry mucous membranes, and reduced urine output. The normal creatinine and electrolytes make significant dehydration unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["New onset tachycardia in a hospitalised patient should prompt consideration of pulmonary embolism.","The Wells score helps risk stratify patients with suspected pulmonary embolism."],"references":["Henning A, Krawiec C. Sinus Tachycardia. [Updated 2023 Mar 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553128/","Imura M, Yamamoto T, Hiasa KI. Pulmonary Thromboembolism Developed During Hospitalization: A Nationwide Retrospective Observational Study Using Claims Data. Cardiol Ther. 2023 Mar;12(1):127-141. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9734681/","Robinson GV. Pulmonary embolism in hospital practice. BMJ. 2006 Jan 21;332(7534):156-60. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1336768/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86869"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15181"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86869"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T14:46:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T14:46:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7872"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104540"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gro